api/OmsiHook.html.title: Namespace OmsiHook | OmsiHook
api/OmsiHook.html.keywords: Namespace OmsiHook Classes D3DMeshFileObject Direct 3D Mesh File, all the metadata relating to a loaded mesh file. D3DMeshObject Direct 3D Mesh object D3DObject Base class for Direct 3D objects D3DTransformObject Base class for transformable Direct 3D objects MemArray<T> Wrapper for Arrays / Lists in OMSI's Memory. MemArray<InternalStruct, Struct> Wrapper for Arrays / Lists in OMSI's Memory. MemArrayBase<Struct> MemArrayString Wrapper for Arrays / Lists in OMSI's Memory. MemArrayStringDict Wrapper for Arrays / Lists in OMSI's Memory with automatic index caching. OmsiActuWeather Settings relating to the real world weather in OMSI OmsiBoolClass Defines a set of conditions based on various data types. OmsiCamera In game camera object OmsiChrono Data store for a map's Chrono Events OmsiChronoChange Base class for Chrono Changes. Chrono changes / events are planned events that a map maker can add to make a map feel more dynamic over time. OmsiChronoChangeDel ChronoChangeDel - no properites defined OmsiChronoChangeLabels List of stringvars relating to a OmsiChronoChange OmsiChronoChangeTyp String refering to the ChronoChange type OmsiComplMapObj Base class for complex map objects - used by vehicles and humans OmsiComplMapObjInst Base class for complex map object instances - such as vehicle instances and human instances OmsiComplMapSceneObjInst Complex scenery object instace data - relating to nightlights, active use... OmsiComplObj More advanced data for complex map objects, such as terrain holes and freetextures OmsiComplObjInst More advanced data for complex map object instances, such as string vars OmsiCoordSystem Defines the shape of a spline in a map OmsiDynHelperMan OmsiFileObject Base class for objects created from files OmsiFileSpline Splines read from a tile file OmsiFileTerrain Defines a tile from a file - including heightmap and sizing OmsiFileWater Data about a tile's water content - similar to OmsiFileTerrain OmsiFreeTexInst Defines a FreeTex instance OmsiFuncClass Defines a curve made of linearly interpolated keyframes - used in const files and similar configuration files OmsiGlobals All recognised Globals in OMSI. OmsiHOF Representation of a HOF / yard / depot File OmsiHook Base OmsiHook class - use this to hook into OMSI's memory and access its data, all the recognised OMSI globals are defined in the Globals property. For example usage see our docs . OmsiHumanBeing Defines a human being. OmsiHumanBeingInst Instance of a OmsiHumanBeing . Instance version store the data that is current (runtime data), wheras the regular OmsiHumanBeing stores the data that has been pulled from disk. OmsiKachelForest Defines a forest on a tile OmsiMap Map object - many global settings can be found here relating to the currently loaded map. OmsiMapKachel A Tile in a Map OmsiMapObjInst Base class for instances of Map Objects OmsiMovingMapObjInst Base Class for all instances of moving map objects - vehicles / humans OmsiObjBlackRect OmsiObjChronoVars Stringvars relating to a chrono event? OmsiObject Base class for all OmsiHook objects - handles some of the memory managment for objects. OmsiPartikel Defines a particle OmsiPartikelEmitter Particle emitter - emits OmsiPartikel OmsiPassengerCabin Defines a passenger cabin (as per the passenger cabin file) OmsiPathGroup A Group of Paths - used in OmsiMapKachel OmsiPathManager Path Manager - used to keep track of paths mostly used by OmsiHumanBeingInst OmsiPathPointBasic Simple Path Point OmsiPathSegment Segment between Path Points OmsiPhysObj Base class for all objects processed by the physics system, all data is read from disk OmsiPhysObjInst Instance of OmsiPhysObj , all the runtime data for a OmsiPhysObj OmsiProgMan Main Program Manager OmsiRemoteMethods All of these methods will only work if called from a native Omsi plugin. These methods also rely on OmsiHookInvoker.dll which must be in the Omsi plugins folder. OmsiRoadVehicle Defines a Road Vehicle - most data is in the .bus/.ovh files OmsiRoadVehicleInst Instance of OmsiRoadVehicle OmsiSound Sound that is playable by OMSI OmsiSoundPack Pack of sounds used by both humans and vehicles OmsiSplineSegment Segment of spline in a tile - splines are a type of mesh that has geometry, in comparison to OmsiPathSegment which defines a track that a vehicle or human can follow, a spline or object can have several paths. api/OmsiHook.MemArray-1.Add.html.title: Method Add | OmsiHook
api/OmsiHook.MemArray-1.Add.html.keywords: Method Add Add(T) Adds an item to the native array. This is slow and might cause memory leaks because it reallocates the whole array. Declaration public override void Add(T item) Parameters Type Name Description T item The item to add to the native array. Overrides OmsiHook.MemArray<T, T>.Add(T) Remarks Since this method doesn't call UpdateFromHook() , if the native array is out of sync with the cached array, then data may be lost when adding new items. In the following case though, it should usually be safe (as long as the native array isn't updated by Omsi while this runs): memArray.UpdateFromHook(); foreach(int item in localObjects) memArray.Add(item);

Remarks This is a heavyweight wrapper for native arrays that provides methods for reading and writing to arrays as well as helping with memory management. For fast, low-level access, use the methods in the OmsiHook.Memory class. For better performance in c# the contents of the wrapped array can be copied to managed memory when constructed or whenever UpdateFromHook() is called. Cached arrays are generally faster when accessed or searched frequently by C#, but they are slower to update and the user is responsible for ensuring that they are synchronised with the native array it wraps. api/OmsiHook.MemArrayStringDict.html.keywords: Class MemArrayStringDict Wrapper for Arrays / Lists in OMSI's Memory with automatic index caching. Inheritance System.Object OmsiObject MemArrayBase < System.String > MemArrayString MemArrayStringDict Implements IDisposable IEnumerable < System.String > ICollection < System.String > IList < System.String > Inherited Members MemArrayString.Item[Int32] MemArrayString.WrappedArray MemArrayString.Wide MemArrayString.Add(String) MemArrayString.Clear() MemArrayString.CopyTo(String[], Int32) MemArrayString.GetEnumerator() MemArrayString.Insert(Int32, String) MemArrayString.RemoveAt(Int32) MemArrayString.Dispose() MemArrayBase<String>.Cached MemArrayBase<String>.Count MemArrayBase<String>.IsReadOnly OmsiObject.Equals(Object) Namespace : OmsiHook Assembly : OmsiHook.dll Syntax public class MemArrayStringDict : MemArrayString, IDisposable, IEnumerable<string>, ICollection<string>, IList<string> Remarks This type of MemArray relies on it being cached and as such no option exists to use it uncached. This is a heavyweight wrapper for native arrays that provides methods for reading and writing to arrays as well as helping with memory management. For fast, low-level access, use the methods in the OmsiHook.Memory class. For better performance in c# the contents of the wrapped array can be copied to managed memory when constructed or whenever UpdateFromHook() is called. Cached arrays are generally faster when accessed or searched frequently by C#, but they are slower to update and the user is responsible for ensuring that they are synchronised with the native array it wraps. articles/building-native-plugins.html.title: Building Native Omsi Plugins | OmsiHook
articles/building-native-plugins.html.keywords:
Building Native Omsi Plugins Some features of OmsiHook such as remote method calls require the library using OmsiHook to be running as a native Omsi plugin. This guide covers some of the basics of building a native Omsi plugin using .NET 5. An example plugin is available at https://github.com/space928/Omsi-Extensions/tree/main/OmsiHookPlugin . Overview of Omsi Plugins DLLs placed in Omsi's \plugins\ folder with an accompanying .opl file will be loaded on startup as plugins. The .opl file is an INI file containing the name of the DLL to load and the ordered lists of variables accessed by the plugin. OPL Files An example .opl file might look like this: [dll] OmsiHookPluginNE.dll [varlist] 1 door_0 [stringvarlist] 3 INEO_DataTransferVehicleNumber INEO_DataTransferDelay INEO_DataTransferPassengerCount [systemvarlist] 4 Time Day Month Year [triggers] 1 bus_doorfront0 The only required tag in the .opl file is the [dll] tag, which specifies the name of the DLL to load. The other tags in this example specify which Omsi variables and triggers to pass to the plugin. The first parameter of each of these tags is the number of variables in the list, followed by the name of each variable, one on each line. DLL Files Omsi requires that plugins export certain methods, all the required methods must be exported (even if they don't do anything) for the plugin to be loaded. Exported methods (C#): [UnmanagedCallersOnly(CallConvs = new[] { typeof(CallConvCdecl) })] public static void PluginStart(IntPtr aOwner) {} [UnmanagedCallersOnly(CallConvs = new[] { typeof(CallConvCdecl) })] public static void PluginFinalize() {} [UnmanagedCallersOnly(CallConvs = new[] { typeof(CallConvCdecl) })] public static void AccessVariable(ushort variableIndex, [C99Type("float*")] IntPtr value, [C99Type("__crt_bool*")] IntPtr writeValue) [UnmanagedCallersOnly(CallConvs = new[] { typeof(CallConvCdecl) })] public static void AccessTrigger(ushort variableIndex, [C99Type("__crt_bool*")] IntPtr triggerScript) { } [UnmanagedCallersOnly(CallConvs = new[] { typeof(CallConvCdecl) })] public static void AccessStringVariable(ushort variableIndex, [C99Type("char*")] IntPtr firstCharacterAddress, [C99Type("__crt_bool*")] IntPtr writeValue) { } [UnmanagedCallersOnly(CallConvs = new[] { typeof(CallConvCdecl) })] public static void AccessSystemVariable(ushort variableIndex, [C99Type("float*")] IntPtr value, [C99Type("__crt_bool*")] IntPtr writeValue) { } In this example, the exported methods have been written in C# with necessary attributes decorating the methods so that they get exported correctly later when we include the native export library. Setting Up a .NET 5 Project to Use as a Plugin Create a new .NET 5 project with an output type of Class Library . Install the DNNE NuGet package. Install the OmsiHook NuGet package. Set the platform target to x86 (Omsi runs exclusively in 32 bit and as such, so must your plugin). Edit your .csproj file to include necessary properties for DNNE to build (see the DNNE github for more details on how to setup native exports): <PropertyGroup> <!-- Platform target must be set to x86 to be loaded by Omsi --> <PlatformTarget>x86</PlatformTarget> </PropertyGroup> <PropertyGroup> <EnableDynamicLoading>true</EnableDynamicLoading> <DnneGenerateExports>true</DnneGenerateExports> <DnneBuildExports>true</DnneBuildExports> <DnneNativeBinaryName></DnneNativeBinaryName> <DnneMSBuildLogging>low</DnneMSBuildLogging> <DnneAddGeneratedBinaryToProject>false</DnneAddGeneratedBinaryToProject> <!-- Enable a workaround for https://github.com/dotnet/sdk/issues/1675 --> <DnneWorkAroundSdk1675>true</DnneWorkAroundSdk1675> <DnneRuntimeIdentifier>win-x86</DnneRuntimeIdentifier> <DnneSelfContained_Experimental>false</DnneSelfContained_Experimental> </PropertyGroup> <Target Name="PostBuild" AfterTargets="PostBuildEvent"> <!-- Optional --> <!-- Copy the built DLLs to the Omsi Plugins folder. NOTE: Make sure the path to Omsi is correct for your machine --> <Exec Command="xcopy "$(SolutionDir)Debug\*.dll" "$(OutDir)" /y
xcopy "$(SolutionDir)Release\*.dll" "$(OutDir)" /y
xcopy "$(OutDir)*.dll" "C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\OMSI 2\plugins\" /y
xcopy "$(OutDir)*.opl" "C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\OMSI 2\plugins\" /y
xcopy "$(OutDir)*.json" "C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\OMSI 2\plugins\" /y" /> </Target> Ensure that you have the correct dependencies installed on your computer to build the project. See: DNNE Requirements . Download Dnne.Attributes.cs and add it to your project. Create your main plugin file and add all the needed exported methods (see DLL Files for an example). Create an .opl file (see OPL Files for an example); The default name of the exported DLL will be <ProjectName>NE.dll ie: for a project called OmsiHookPlugin , the DLL will be OmsiHookPluginNE.dll . This can be customised using the DNNE project properties. Build your project! If everything was done correctly your Omsi plugins folder should now contain at least: <ProjectName>.dll <ProjectName>NE.dll OmsiHook.dll <ProjectName>.opl <ProjectName>.runtimeconfig.json If you use remote method calls: OmsiHookInvoker.dll

articles/intro.html.title: OmsiHook Documentation | OmsiHook
articles/intro.html.keywords: OmsiHook Documentation Getting Started Download the NuGet package https://www.nuget.org/packages/OmsiHook/ Start using OmsiHook using OmsiHook; class Program { static void Main(string[] args) { // Create an OmsiHook and attach to any running instance of Omsi OmsiHook.OmsiHook omsi = new(); omsi.AttachToOMSI(); while (true) { // Get the PlayerVehicle and get its position var pos = omsi.Globals.PlayerVehicle.Position; // Print the position to the console Console.WriteLine($"Player vehicle pos: x:{pos.x:F3}\ty:{pos.y:F3}\tz:{pos.z:F3}"); Thread.Sleep(500); } } }

index.html.title: OmsiHook Documentation | OmsiHook
index.html.keywords: OmsiHook Documentation Omsi hooking and modding sdk. The dead simple way to hook into Omsi and fiddle with it's memory. In it's current state we only have mappings for a limited number of Omsi objects, but it's easy to extend. Allows both reading and writing data from Omsi in real time, but currently doesn't allow for anything that requires memory allocation (eg: adding elements to arrays). The library makes use of C# properties and classes to wrap native Omsi objects making them simple to interact with in a managed environment. Check out the API docs for specifics on how to use the library. Usage Example Here's a quick example of how to use it. using OmsiHook; class Program { static void Main(string[] args) { // Create an OmsiHook and attach to any running instance of Omsi OmsiHook.OmsiHook omsi = new(); omsi.AttachToOMSI(); while (true) { // Get the PlayerVehicle and get its position var pos = omsi.Globals.PlayerVehicle.Position; // Print the position to the console Console.WriteLine($"Player vehicle pos: x:{pos.x:F3}\ty:{pos.y:F3}\tz:{pos.z:F3}"); Thread.Sleep(500); } } }
